69
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:05,375
The mechanism for climate change

70
00:03:05,375 --> 00:03:07,040
is the greenhouse effect.

71
00:03:07,040 --> 00:03:09,680
What happens here
is that the sun

72
00:03:09,680 --> 00:03:11,390
shines down on the Earth and so

73
00:03:11,390 --> 00:03:13,145
sends energy, and light,

74
00:03:13,145 --> 00:03:14,850
and heat into the Earth,

75
00:03:14,850 --> 00:03:18,470
and then the Earth's surface
absorbs that and re-emits

76
00:03:18,470 --> 00:03:22,750
that back as long wave
or heat radiation.

77
00:03:22,750 --> 00:03:24,500
It's a different
form of radiation,

78
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:27,080
which means that
greenhouse gases in

79
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:30,290
the atmosphere absorb
that and then they,

80
00:03:30,290 --> 00:03:31,895
in turn, re-emit it.

81
00:03:31,895 --> 00:03:33,860
Some of it goes out
into space and some of

82
00:03:33,860 --> 00:03:36,175
it goes back to the
Earth's surface.

83
00:03:36,175 --> 00:03:38,260
This is generally
useful for us and

84
00:03:38,260 --> 00:03:40,135
lets us be alive because

85
00:03:40,135 --> 00:03:42,820
those greenhouse gases
keep the surface of

86
00:03:42,820 --> 00:03:46,580
the Earth warm enough for us
to function, which we like.

87
00:03:46,580 --> 00:03:50,290
But as we can see
in recent time,

88
00:03:50,290 --> 00:03:54,525
there have been much higher
anthropogenic CO_2 emissions

89
00:03:54,525 --> 00:03:56,170
and so that is leading

90
00:03:56,170 --> 00:03:59,170
to a warming of the Earth's
atmosphere that is much

91
00:03:59,170 --> 00:04:03,050
higher than many of us can
adapt to in many ways.

92
00:04:03,050 --> 00:04:06,550
Impacts to date first on
just the temperature,

93
00:04:06,550 --> 00:04:08,155
we can look at the
global warming

94
00:04:08,155 --> 00:04:10,480
relative to a time
period before we

95
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:11,935
had omitted so much

96
00:04:11,935 --> 00:04:14,995
CO_2 and other greenhouse
gases into the atmosphere.

97
00:04:14,995 --> 00:04:18,640
Compared to that time
period of 1850-1900,

98
00:04:18,640 --> 00:04:20,605
we can see that, at first,

99
00:04:20,605 --> 00:04:22,540
there were just the
normal oscillations,

100
00:04:22,540 --> 00:04:23,800
right around the 1960s,

101
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:25,825
there were just the normal
temperature oscillations,

102
00:04:25,825 --> 00:04:28,790
but then we can see a
clear trend upward.

103
00:04:28,790 --> 00:04:30,770
Those oscillations continued but

104
00:04:30,770 --> 00:04:32,510
the average moved upward.

105
00:04:32,510 --> 00:04:35,930
Something to notice here
is that the model or

106
00:04:35,930 --> 00:04:39,345
estimated anthropogenic
warming is

107
00:04:39,345 --> 00:04:40,760
tracking well with

108
00:04:40,760 --> 00:04:44,000
the observed monthly global
mean surface temperature,

109
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:45,920
the observed averages
are matching

110
00:04:45,920 --> 00:04:49,460
modeled averages based on

111
00:04:49,460 --> 00:04:52,315
climate change in the
mechanism that I explained.

112
00:04:52,315 --> 00:04:57,185
In terms of long-term impacts
on this temporal scale.

113
00:04:57,185 --> 00:04:58,610
These could be variable,

114
00:04:58,610 --> 00:05:00,725
so it depends how
humans respond,

115
00:05:00,725 --> 00:05:02,720
and has large uncertainties due

116
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:04,870
to the complex system
of the atmosphere.

117
00:05:04,870 --> 00:05:06,500
If there's no reduction,

118
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:09,710
we're likely to exceed this
threshold right here of

119
00:05:09,710 --> 00:05:13,900
1.5 degrees of warming and
could even reach two degrees.

120
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:17,070
But with faster CO_2
reductions were likely to stay

121
00:05:17,070 --> 00:05:19,010
below 1.5 degrees
of warming and we

122
00:05:19,010 --> 00:05:21,890
