166
00:07:03,260 --> 00:07:06,005
such as glaciers or
coastal erosion.

167
00:07:06,005 --> 00:07:09,305
In green, we've got our
biological systems,

168
00:07:09,305 --> 00:07:13,205
so things like wildfire
and marine ecosystems.

169
00:07:13,205 --> 00:07:16,555
Then in red, we've got
human and managed systems,

170
00:07:16,555 --> 00:07:18,530
so things like food production

171
00:07:18,530 --> 00:07:21,200
or livestock or
health and economies.

172
00:07:21,200 --> 00:07:23,300
You can see blue, green,
and red throughout.

173
00:07:23,300 --> 00:07:26,015
If you want to dig
deeper into this,

174
00:07:26,015 --> 00:07:30,020
you can also see the confidence
range for all of these.

175
00:07:30,020 --> 00:07:32,300
You can see relatively
high confidence

176
00:07:32,300 --> 00:07:33,710
that climate change is impacting

177
00:07:33,710 --> 00:07:36,590
every continent and
the many systems

178
00:07:36,590 --> 00:07:38,965
that we use in living.

179
00:07:38,965 --> 00:07:41,415
What about future risks?

180
00:07:41,415 --> 00:07:43,070
These depend on the future

181
00:07:43,070 --> 00:07:44,720
of our greenhouse gas emissions.

182
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:46,415
I'm going to go
through this figure

183
00:07:46,415 --> 00:07:47,450
backwards a little bit,

184
00:07:47,450 --> 00:07:50,600
starting at Panel C. At Panel C,

185
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:53,480
we can see that our
baseline emissions

186
00:07:53,480 --> 00:07:55,310
are in gray at the top-right,

187
00:07:55,310 --> 00:07:57,650
that's how much
were predicted to

188
00:07:57,650 --> 00:08:00,230
emit in greenhouse gases
if there's no change.

189
00:08:00,230 --> 00:08:02,600
But there are
different scenarios

190
00:08:02,600 --> 00:08:04,655
that are in the IPCC report,

191
00:08:04,655 --> 00:08:07,130
all of which would lead
to varying levels of

192
00:08:07,130 --> 00:08:09,530
reduced greenhouse
gas emissions,

193
00:08:09,530 --> 00:08:12,170
and so what the
rest of this figure

194
00:08:12,170 --> 00:08:13,310
does is look at those

195
00:08:13,310 --> 00:08:15,110
different scenarios
and their impacts.

196
00:08:15,110 --> 00:08:18,140
In Panel B, what we
can see is that if we

197
00:08:18,140 --> 00:08:21,080
are able to reduce our
greenhouse gas emissions,

198
00:08:21,080 --> 00:08:22,220
then that would reduce

199
00:08:22,220 --> 00:08:24,745
the cumulative
emissions over time.

200
00:08:24,745 --> 00:08:27,735
It would go from around 8,000

201
00:08:27,735 --> 00:08:31,290
